{{Citation needed|date=June 8, 2012}}
{{Expand Japanese}}
[[File:Yamanobe-no-michi02s3200.jpg|thumb|280px|Yamanobe-no-Michi near {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.]]
[[File:山の辺の道 - panoramio (1).jpg|thumb|280px|Yamanobe-no-Michi]]

'''Yamanobe-no-Michi''' (山辺の道, {{small|Ancient Pronunciation}}: Yamanobe-no-Michi, {{small|Classical Writing}}: '''山辺道''', {{small|Old-Character Style}}: '''山邊道''') is one of {{ill|Japan's ancient roads|ja|日本の古道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and a representative example of {{ill|Yamato's ancient roads|ja|大和の古道|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It refers to a road that traversed the foothills of ancient {{ill|Yamato|ja|大和|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (a region known as Yamanobe, the origin of {{ill|Yamanobe District|ja|山辺郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}). It is recognized as the '''oldest road in Japanese history''' and as the '''oldest existing road in Japan'''{{sfn|Asai Kenji|2001|p=82}}{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=136}}.

The road runs from the foothills of {{ill|Mount Miwa|ja|三輪山|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in the southeast of the {{ill|Nara Basin|ja|奈良盆地|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, to the foothills of {{ill|Kasuga Mountain|ja|春日山|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in the northeast. It follows the eastern edge of the basin, skirting the foothills along the Kasuga Fault Escarpment in a north-south direction.

Though some local government authorities use the variant spelling "Yama-no-be no Michi" (山の辺の道), it does not adhere to historical or {{ill|toponymy|ja|地名学|qq=draft|qq=draft}} conventions. In contrast, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|qq=draft|qq=draft}} uses the classical spelling "Yamanobe-michi" or "Yamabe-michi"{{efn|Example: The Imperial Household Agency manages {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}} such as {{ill|Andon'yama Kofun|ja|行燈山古墳|1=Andon-yama Kofun|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, officially referred to as "Yamabe-michi Makari-no-Oka Kami-no-Misasagi" (山辺道勾岡上陵)}}.

== Overview ==

The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft}} includes the following reference in the section about Emperor Sujin:

{{Quotation|The imperial mausoleum was constructed along the Yamabe-no-Michi.|Nihon Shoki, Emperor Sujin Chapter}}

This indicates that Yamanobe-no-Michi was established before Emperor Sujin's mausoleum was built.

Additionally, the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}} contains similar descriptions in its accounts of Emperors Sujin and Keikō. These descriptions further support the idea that Yamanobe-no-Michi had already been established during the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (4th century CE){{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=136}}.

Archaeological findings suggest that it may have existed as early as the late {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, connecting the {{ill|Furu Ruins|ja|布留遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Makimuku ruins|ja|纏向遺跡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

[[File:Yamanobe-no-michi01s3872.jpg|thumb|270px|A monument inscribed with a {{ill|Man'yōshū|ja|万葉集|qq=draft|qq=draft}} poem by {{ill|Kakinomoto no Hitomaro|ja|柿本人麻呂|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Located in {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.]]
[[File:Wanishita Shrine (Ichinomoto) Kagehime Poem.jpg|thumb|180px|A monument commemorating Kagehime's song along the road near {{ill|Wanishita Shrine (Tenri)|lt=Wanishita Shrine|ja|和爾下神社_(天理市)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Tenri City.]]

Stretching approximately 35 kilometers and measuring less than 2 meters wide, the road passes through key historical sites such as {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōmiwa Shrine|ja|大神神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and the {{ill|Imperial mausoleums of Emperor Sujin and Emperor Keikō|ja|天皇陵|1=Japanese imperial tombs|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. These features highlight its importance as a cultural and political thoroughfare{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|pp=137–138}}{{sfn|Asai Kenji|2015|p=107}}.

=== Course ===

The modern hiking route, approximately 15 kilometers long, is a part of the [[:en:Tōkai_Nature_Trail|Tōkai Nature Trail]]. It is particularly popular between Isonokami Shrine in {{ill|Tenri|ja|天理市|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and Ōmiwa Shrine in {{ill|Sakurai|ja|桜井市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The northern section of the ancient road is less defined due to erosion over time{{sfn|Rom International (ed.)|2005|p=137}}.

== Notable Sites and Historic Landmarks Along the Route ==
* {{ill|Isonokami Shrine|ja|石上神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Ruins of Uchiyama Eikyū-ji|ja|内山永久寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Yamato Shrine|ja|大和神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Nishiyamazuka Kofun|ja|西山塚古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Chōgaku-ji|ja|長岳寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Tomb of Emperor Sujin|ja|崇神天皇陵|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
